# First model - Linear Regression
# Summary statistics
```{r}
lin_reg_model1 <- lm(win.pct ~ (.-year -Id),data=training_data)

summary(lin_reg_model1)
```

# Residual diagnostics
```{r}
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(lin_reg_model1)
```
The residuals seem to be pretty normalized, but we will test them just to be safe.

# Confirmation on normality
```{r}
# lambda parameter expands the x-axis on the graph
MASS::boxcox(lin_reg_model1, lambda = seq(-2, 4))
```
Since the boxcox plot is yielding a lambda value between 1 and 2, we will test to see if the strength of our model increases if we were to treat lambda = 2 (response squared transformation). We have already tested our model for when lambda = 1 (no transformation on the response variable).

# Linear regression model w/ response squared transformation
```{r}
lin_reg_model11 <- lm((win.pct^2) ~ (.-year -Id),data=training_data)

summary(lin_reg_model11)
```
Since the adjusted R-squared value of this transformed model is 0.5343 and this value of lin_reg_model1 is 0.5345, we will move forward with the initial model as the stronger of the two.

# Initial regression model, removing statistically insignificant predictors (predictors with a p-value > 0.1)
```{r}
lin_reg_model2 <- lm(win.pct ~ `R/G`+G+`1B`+SO+BA+GDP+IBB,data=training_data)

summary(lin_reg_model2)
```
This model is worse than lin_reg_model1 with respect to Adjusted R-squared. Onto the next model!

# Initial regression model, removing statistically insignificant predictors (predictors with a p-value > 0.1) AND a response squared transformation
```{r}
lin_reg_model21 <- lm((win.pct^2) ~ `R/G`+G+`1B`+SO+BA+GDP+IBB,data=training_data)

summary(lin_reg_model21)
```
Though this model has an adjusted R-squared value of 0.4878 which is stronger than that of lin_reg_model2, it is still considerably weaker than lin_reg_model1.

# Initial regression model, with more strict removing of statistically insignificant predictors (predictors with a p-value > 0.05)
```{r}
lin_reg_model3 <- lm(win.pct ~ `R/G`+G+SO+BA+IBB,data=training_data)

summary(lin_reg_model3)
```
With respect to Adjusted R-squared this model is the poorest at predicting our response.

# Initial regression model, with more strict removing of statistically insignificant predictors (predictors with a p-value > 0.05) AND a response squared transformation
```{r}
lin_reg_model31 <- lm((win.pct^2) ~ `R/G`+G+SO+BA+IBB,data=training_data)

summary(lin_reg_model31)
```
Though this model has a multiple R-squared value of 0.4871 which is stronger than that of lin_reg_model3, it is still considerably weaker than lin_reg_model1.

# Since our initial model with all inputs and no transformation on the response has the strongest Adjusted R-squared value, we will use this version of our linear regression model to perform 10 fold Cross-Validation.
```{r}
# calling other libraries here because they cause masking issues when placed in libraries.R script above
library(glmnet)
library(gam)
library(tree)
library(randomForest)
library(gbm)
library(ISLR)
library(boot)
library(FNN)
library(class)
library(MASS)
```

```{r}
set.seed(24)
glm.fit <- glm(win.pct ~ (.-year -Id),data=training_data)
cv.errors <- cv.glm(training_data, glm.fit,K = 10) #K-fold K
lmcvfit <- cv.errors$delta[2]
lmcvfit
```
It can be seen that our Cross-Validation Mean Squared Error = 0.003090097.
This means that our Root Mean Squared Error = sqrt(0.003090097) = 0.0555886 = 5.6%
Hence, predictions are typically within about 5.6 percentage points of actual team win percentage, or roughly 9.1 wins (0.056 * 162) over a 162-game season.

# Predictions on our test data
```{r}
# predictions on test data
lin_reg_model1.predictions <- predict(lin_reg_model1,test_data)
# testing mean squared error
mse_test <- mean((lin_reg_model1.predictions - test_data$win.pct)^2)
mse_test
# root mean squared error
rmse_test <- sqrt(mse_test)
rmse_test
# how much error in terms of games per regular season
rmse_test * 162
```
It can be seen that our Test Mean Squared Error = 0.002734173.
This means that our Root Mean Squared Error = sqrt(0.002734173) = 0.05228932 = 5.2%
Hence, predictions are typically within about 5.2 percentage points of actual team win percentage, or roughly 8.4 wins (0.052 * 162) over a 162-game season.

If test error and CV error are similar, then the model generalizes well. If the test error is higher (worse), then the model is overfit to the training data.

Cross-validation helps you build the model.
The test set helps you trust the model.

