# Next model - Random Forest
# Random forest cross validation and search for optimal number of predictors
```{r}
library(caret)
library(randomForest)

set.seed(24)

train_control <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 5
)

rf_model <- train(
  win.pct ~ (.-year -Id),
  data = training_data,
  method = "rf",
  trControl = train_control,
  ntree = 1000,
  tuneLength = 5
)

rf_model

rf_model$results
```
We can see after running some 5-fold cross-validation, the mtry value (number of predictors that are randomly selected amongst all 24) with the most optimal (lowest) root mean squared error is 13. Said differently, during our cross-validation it was determined that our random forest model that was best at predicting win percentage was the model in which each individual decision tree of our 1000 trees contained a random grouping of 13 of our 24 total predictor variables. Additionally, our runner-ups with respect to RMSE were 18 variables, followed by all 24, then 7 and 2.

It can be seen that our Cross-Validation Root Mean Squared Error = 0.05750514 = 5.75%
Hence, predictions are typically within about 5.75 percentage points of actual team win percentage, or roughly 9.3 wins (0.0575 * 162) over a 162-game season.


# Checking the node purity of mtry = 13 random forest model
```{r}
set.seed(24) 
# renaming variables that randomForest() is having issues with
rand_forest_df <- training_data |>
  rename(R.G = `R/G`, singles = `1B`, doubles = `2B`, triples = `3B`)
randforest_model <- randomForest(win.pct ~ (.-year -Id), data = rand_forest_df, ntree = 1000, mtry = 13, importance = TRUE)

importance(randforest_model)

varImpPlot(randforest_model)
```
Within this Random Forest model, we can see from the Percent Increase in Mean Squared Error (%IncMSE) among our predictors, On Base Percentage (OBP) is our largest value. This means that for a given decision tree within our random forest, as predictor variable combinations are shifting around from tree-to-tree, when the OBP variable is removed from one tree to the next, those 2 trees see the greatest decrease in predictive power than any other change in predictors. Conversely, we can see that the average batter age (BatAge) predictor variable has the smallest %IncMSE value.

Within this Random Forest model, we can see from the Increase in Node Purity (IncNodePurity) among our predictors, On Base Percentage (OBP) is a clear front runner. This means that OBP is the best predictor variable at determining a split in a given decision tree within the random forest model. To come as not much of a surprise, conversely the games played (G) predictor has the smallest increase in node purity. Though it should be noted that the IncNodePurity metric is biased towards 1) continuous variables, and 2) variables with much variance; therefore, this Increase in Node Purity should be viewed with caution with respect to predictive power.

# Predictions on our test data
```{r}
y <- test_data |>
  rename(R.G = `R/G`, singles = `1B`, doubles = `2B`, triples = `3B`)
randforest_preds <- predict(randforest_model, y)
randforest_mse <- mean((randforest_preds-y$win.pct)**2)
randforest_rmse <- sqrt(randforest_mse)
randforest_rmse
```
It can be seen that our Test Root Mean Squared Error = 0.05699896 = 5.7%
Hence, predictions are typically within about 5.7 percentage points of actual team win percentage, or roughly 9.2 wins (0.057 * 162) over a 162-game season.

